post_text:
Over the last two weeks, NYS has withheld more than $200,000 in aid to the Morrisville-Eaton CSD. We expect this number could grow to more than $2 million by the end of the year. Currently, school districts have been told this is just a withholding while the state awaits federal assistance. Some legislators have signaled that this withholding could become permanent.

MECS cannot sustain a 20% reduction in aid without great sacrifice. A Thought Exchange has been posted here: https://my.thoughtexchange.com/753174109 which will help us capture the sentiment of the community as we prepare for the most challenging fiscal times of our lifetimes.

Please take a few moments to provide your thoughts and rate the thoughts of others.

post_text:
On Thursday, September 3, 2020, the Upstate University mammography van will be here from 9 AM to 3 PM! This opportunity is open to MECS staff as well as the community. Click on the link below or call 315-464-2582 to schedule an appointment. Any specific questions regarding your appointment and procedures can be directed to the staff at Upstate. Appointments can also be requested online at: http://www.upstate.edu/mobile-mammography/
To be eligible for a mammogram on the van, women should be 40 years and older; not have had a mammogram in the past 12 months; and not be experiencing breast problems. An order from your doctor is required at the time of service. The staff at Upstate University can help coordinate that with your doctor if needed.
The van, funded by a New York State Department of Health grant, is part of Gov. Cuomo’s “Get Screened, No Excuses” Breast Cancer Initiative, which is aimed at getting rid of obstacles to breast cancer screening for women in New York.

post_text: The attached is a message shared this morning via School Messenger regarding the District's Reopening plan for the fall. The plan we want to implement allows students who desire to return to school full-time to do that and those looking for a remote setting the opportunity for that too. This vision requires many stars to align in the coming weeks including our ability to maintain social distancing, transport children to the schools, have enough staff available to deliver in-person instruction, and much more. There are several other models that can be found in our Reopening Plan if the ideal return to school glitches. The full plan can be found by visiting: www.m-ecs.org and clicking the "Reopening Plan 2020" link. Be well, Go Warriors!

post_text: It is my pleasure to recognize Alexis LaFever and Jackson Ford as Morrisville-Eaton’s Section III Scholar Athletes. Due to current restrictions the Section III Executive Committee held a drive thru ceremony for all those around the Section that were to be recognized. On Thursday June 11th Alexis and Jackson traveled to the Section office to accept the award with their family. It was my pleasure to meet them there and present them with this award. Section III was also able to put the awards ceremony on CW6 on Monday night. Here is the link for the ceremony that recognized all scholar athletes from around the Section https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bdnh-N5NQZ4&feature=youtu.be . Congratulations Alexis and Jackson.

post_text: With all these sports highlights, we would be remiss if we did not honor retiring coaching legend, Duane LeBlanc. Duane helped shape the wrestling and soccer programs. He brought home multiple Sectional and State titles. He is well respected by his coaching peers around the leagues. Duane has given huge amounts of personal time, finances (pitching in for apparel and other things some kids needed), organized multiple summer camps, tournaments, clinics, and provided great learning opportunities for our kids over the years. You couldn't ask for a better mentor for our student athletes. Duane - thanks for giving your heart to so many kids...

Another item is our planned last day of school. As long as a new executive order is not issued changing our plans, the last day will be June 16th. Plans for students to pick up their belongings and drop off school property will be communicated in the coming weeks.

Have a Happy Memorial Weekend. Please remember that classes on Monday are cancelled and all school buildings will be closed.

Stay Healthy!

post_text:
Uncertainty of the Budget Vote and Elections -
School elections are statutorily required to be held on the third Tuesday in May. However, under Executive Order 202.13, issued by Governor Cuomo on March 30, 2020, school elections were formally postponed “until at least June 1, 2020, and subject to further directive as to the timing, location or manner of voting for such elections. The New York State School Boards Association has obtained informal guidance from the Deputy Secretary for Education in New York that the Order was intended to cover not just school board “elections” but also school board “votes” in general, such as the District’s annual budget vote that had been scheduled to occur on May 19, 2020. In short, like many other events across the State, school elections have been placed on pause. In the meantime, we have deferred initial publication (or any further publication) of the District’s annual vote notice until such time as a date for the District’s annual vote has been established. We will update you as information comes available.

post_text:
It is with a heavy heart that I share that MECS senior, Jordan Burke, passed away as a result of injuries sustained in a motor vehicle accident in the early morning hours of April 14th. Please keep Jordan and his family in your thoughts and prayers during this very difficult time. Jordan was a contributing member of the varsity football and basketball teams.

The district will be working with local officials to develop a plan to support those grieving the loss of this incredible young man. If you or someone you know is in need of counseling, please reach out to Mrs. Anderalli, Mrs. Cesta, or Mrs. Kempton. Their e-mail addresses are as follows: janderalli@m-ecs.org, mcesta@m-ecs.org, and skempton@m-ecs.org

Jordan was an incredible Warrior who will be sorely missed…

post_text:
So many selfless people in our community have offered to lend a hand through this pandemic. You are all amazing, and thank you! With so many moving parts and unknowns, it is often hard to identify where the help can be directed. The American Red Cross, however, has a need that the residents of the district, and beyond, can help fill. A Blood Drive is set for Thursday April 9th. Please call 1-800-RED CROSS (1-800-733-2767) or visit RedCrossBlood.org
and enter: morrisvllecommunitych to schedule an appointment.

post_text:
In response to the COVID-19 Pandemic and the declaration of a State of Emergency effecting a large number of our students, MECS will be operating on a half-day, Monday March 16th. M/H will dismiss at 10:47, Elementary will dismiss at noon. There are no BOCES classes on Monday. All Classes will be cancelled from March 17th - April 13th. Please refer to the letter posted on www.m-ecs.org

Efforts will be made to provide students access to educational resources and meals during the shutdown time. Teachers will be active during this period working on ways to deliver the best quality materials possible. This is a great challenge for all of us and we have a lot of work to do in order to serve our children best under these circumstances.

Stay healthy...

post_text: I’d like to highlight our partnership with Greenheart Exchange (www.greenheartexchange.org) bringing exchange students to MECS, including Sehan from Korea & Gustavo from Brazil here now. Greenheart is looking for potential host families for the 20-21 school year, keeping in mind that they are volunteers who cannot be compensated under strict J1 visa US State Department regulations. post_text: Please, please, help keep our children safe and stop for stopped school buses!
shared_text:
Norwich City School District
May 7, 2019 at 9:51 PM ·

TOUCHED BY AN ANGEL
This is exactly why you should NEVER pass a school bus when the stop arm is out and the red lights are flashing!

Quick-thinking, fast-acting #Norwich bus driver Samantha Call prevented an almost-certain tragedy from occurring at 10:44 a.m. Friday, April 26, on State Route 12.

Click the #video to watch the six-year NCSD driver stop a student just short of disaster, grabbing the boy from behind as a car whizzes by the open school bus doors.

"Samantha did an outstanding job," NCSD Transportation Supervisor William Loomis said. "All of our drivers undergo continuous training so they're prepared to handle situations like this. We hope this video helps everyone to realize the dangers of passing a stopped school bus."
#IAmNorwich #PurplePride #GoNorwich #HeroBusDriver #SchoolBusSafety2019
